[[Unbase]] will have many many concurrencies across a system which must be efficiently converged if the system is to function

The convergence of these concurrencies must be able to occur in a pairwise fashion, and in orders which are unpredictable

the "Final" converged [[Memo]] must arrive at the same identity as (and collide, be isomorphic to, idempotent with) other final converged Memos which were arrived at by different orderings and pairings of concurrent memos and their intermediates
How do we do this efficiently?
Do we utilize lexicographic ordering of N-wise concurrent memos (and their concurrent N-wise intermediates) to power an associative N-wise convergence process?
This should work, but the requirement of lexicographic ordering may reduce the efficiency of the convergence proces

One way to think of it is like tent poles:
Putting up a single pole doesn't tell you very much about the tent's shape.
Putting up the second pole tells you a little more about it's shape.
Putting up the third pole tells you a LOT about its shape.
Putting up the fourth pole tells you more about the tent's shape, but not quite as much as the third

Obviously a tent being a three dimensional structure, the third tent pole is the most valuable. Other intellectual edifices will have a differing numbers of useful dimensions for tracing their contours, but I think the principle may generalize.

What is it?

From Epistemology / Symbol Manipulation: **Every instance of every thing, thought, abstract entity, or event in the observable universe, is a Symbol**
These are symbols too, but they represent an astronomically small subset of existent symbols
Written and Spoken Language represent the smallest set of symbols, which through sociological processes, have taken on a loosely agreed upon meaning.
Arguably Culture itself is a [[Teche]] for the establishment of a common symbolic subset which may be used to convey ideas in a (lossy) but functional fashion
